<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Groups Condemn U.S. Acts on Peninsula </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Groups Condemn U.S. Acts on Peninsula </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0704154094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1516 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0704154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Moves Against DPRK Condemned Abroad" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 7 (KCNA) -- Public organizations of 
different countries denounced the anti-DPRK acts of the United 
States which reversed the agreed conclusions reached at the 
DPRK-U.S. contact in New York and is aggravating the situation 
on the Korean peninsula. 
  The Committee for Supporting Korea's Reunification, the 
Peace 
Action Committee and 14 other organizations of Nepal in a joint 
statement criticized the United States for reversing its 
commitment and massing its Armed Forces around the Korean 
peninsula in a hasty move to resume the "Team Spirit" joint 
military exercises and deploy Patriot missiles in South Korea, 
in disregard of the expectations and hope of the world public. 
  The statement strongly urged the United States to desist 
from 
complicating the situation of the Korean peninsula any longer by 
sincerely implementing its commitment to the DPRK on the 
principles of the DPRK-U.S. joint statement, not going against 
the trend of the times. The Jordanian Committee for Solidarity 
with the Korean People in a statement voiced opposition to the 
U.S. interference in the internal affairs of Korea, urging an 
immediate halt to the frantic anti-DPRK campaign. 
  The Central Committee of the Organization of Workers of 
Mozambique in a statement denounced as unreasonable and unfair 
the act of the United States and the International Atomic Energy 
Agency in transferring the "nuclear issue" to the UN Security 
Council. 
  The National Liberation War Veterans Committee of Zimbabwe 
demanded in a letter to the U.S. chief executive that the United 
States to [halt] at once it preparations for a war of 
aggression and embark on a negotiated settlement of the nuclear 
issue on the Korean peninsula. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

