<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   China `Will Oppose' Sanctions Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    China `Will Oppose' Sanctions Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804050494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0405 GMT 8 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0804050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Liu Shuqing, president of the Chinese People's 
Institute of Foreign Affairs, who is visiting the ROK, said 
today that China will oppose to resolve the North Korean nuclear 
issue by applying sanctions, stressing that to take a 
countermove of sanctions against North Korea will only 
complicate the issue. 
  President Liu came to Seoul to hold discussions with the ROK 
on the detail of forming the ROK-PRC Forum, which will be 
inaugurated in June. His remarks attract the public eye because 
he is a core person in charge of China's diplomacy who was vice 
foreign minister and occupied other important posts. 
  President Liu asked back if any problem had ever been 
resolved through international sanctions and said that, although 
the North Korean nuclear issue had occasionally faced obstacles, 
progress was truly made in resolving the issue through dialogue 
between North Korea and the United States and between North 
Korea and the International Atomic Energy Agency. He continued 
to say that on the ground of this progress, China believes 
firmly [hwaksin] that the North Korean nuclear issue will be 
resolved through dialogue. 
  President Liu also said that he had met North Korean 
President Kim Il-song many times, but he would not play the role 
of a mediator between South and North Korea for resolving the 
nuclear issue because there are dialogue channels between the 
two. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

