<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Cites AFP on U.S. Comment on MIA's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Cites AFP on U.S. Comment on MIA's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0704122694 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1100 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0704122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to AFP, the U.S. State Department on 6 
April issued a statement asserting that U.S. teams did not find 
any signs of American servicemen being alive in the 10 detention 
camps that the U.S. side had inspected over the past six weeks. 
The statement rejected the allegations made by the three 
American citizens who left Vietnam on 3 April that U.S. 
inspectors were not allowed to have access to Vietnamese 
prisons. The U.S. State Department statement asserted that 
members of the Hanoi-based Task Force for U.S. Servicemen 
Missing in Action had asked for permission to visit ten 
detention camps in six weeks and had been allowed to go to all 
of those camps. 

</TEXT>

