<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   OECD Head Discusses Japanese, World Economies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OECD Head Discusses Japanese, World Economies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704150794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 6 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0704150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with OECD Secretary General Jean-Claude Paye by </F>
unidentified NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN reporter in Tokyo on 5 April; 
first paragraph is NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN introduction] 
  [Text] OECD Secretary General Jean-Claude Paye gave an 
interview to a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN reporter in Tokyo on 5 
April, during which he pointed out that "there are signs of 
economic recovery in Japan." However, he also expressed concern 
that if the value of the yen continues to appreciate, exports 
will stop growing, and there might be a delay in economic 
recovery. He indicated that to expand domestic demand, "the 
Japanese Government should implement income tax reductions for 
more than one year." Paye also stated during an interview with 
KYODO NEWS AGENCY reporters at the Japan National Press Club 
that the estimated real economic growth rate of the 24 OECD 
members in 1994 (averaging 2.1 percent) "will probably be 
revised upward in June." 
  The following is a summary of the interview with Paye: 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How do you look at the present world 
economic situation? 
  [Paye] It is heading in a good direction. The U.S. economy 
is expanding, and the economies of Britain, Canada, and the 
other English-speaking OECD members are turning for the better. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What do you think of the Japanese 
economic situation? 
  [Paye] The economy has hit bottom. Certain signs of 
recovery can now be observed. If the yen exchange rate remains 
stable, economic recovery can actually be seen within this year. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Are you thinking of revising the 
December 1993 projection of economic growth rate of the 24 OECD 
member states? 
  [Paye] We are working on it, and hope to do that in June. 
Considering the economic expansion in the United States, we may 
have to revise the previous estimate slightly upward. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What do you think is the appropriate 
yen exchange rate? 
  [Paye] It is hard to pinpoint such an exchange rate. 
However, if yen appreciation goes any further, exports will 
suffer, and this may delay economic recovery. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What steps do you think the Japanese 
Government should take to expand domestic demand? 
  [Paye] It will be important to implement income tax 
reductions for more than one year. Some people say the reduced 
taxes will only go into savings, but these savings should be 
used in investment to stimulate more domestic demand. 
  Furthermore, to build a consumer-oriented economy, it will 
be 
necessary to actively relax government regulations. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] The United States is asking for 
numerical targets to increase Japan's imports as the solution to 
bilateral trade frictions. 
  [Paye] I am against unilateral measures, and laying down 
trade rules through bilateral negotiations. I can understand 
that the enormous U.S. trade deficit is a problem, but the 
solution has to follow multilateral trade rules. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What will be the major items on the 
agenda of the OECD ministerial meeting in June? 
  [Paye] There are three major agenda items. First, 
employment. Second, building a better multilateral framework to 
deal with economic globalization. Third, promoting cooperation 
with China, Russia and other nonmember states. I am looking 
forward to the ROK's membership in the OECD in the near future. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] In relation to employment, the 
European countries are critical that the economic growth in 
Asian countries is built on sacrifices resulting from low wages 
paid to the workers. 
  [Paye] The question of wage level is not a problem for the 
OECD, but should be discussed mainly by the International Labor 
Organization (ILO). However, personally, I do not think we 
should penalize a country for having a wage level lower than the 
average wages in OECD countries. Even though such countries may 
enjoy a temporary advantage over the advanced nations in terms 
of wages, such an advantage will be lost quite rapidly with 
economic growth. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

