<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Vague' Terms Plague Phone Accord With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Vague' Terms Plague Phone Accord With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704172994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0704172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It has been learned that in an agreement statement 
for the Japan-U.S. negotiations on mobile phones released by the 
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications on 6 April, there is an 
expression that might be interpreted as that the Japanese 
Government has guaranteed the implementation of the agreement. 
  The expression in question is the word "oversee" used in an 
official statement written in English. The word is used in the 
expression that the Japanese Government will "oversee" [kantoku] 
to help the Nippon Idou Tsushin Corporation [Japan Mobile 
Communications Corporation] (IDO) complete actions to enlarge 
the U.S. Motorola-compatible mobile phone system. In its 
Japanese- language version tentatively translated from the 
English original released on the same day, the Ministry of Posts 
and Telecommunications translated the word "oversee" as "watch 
it to the end" ["mitodokeru"], thus using a weaker nuance than 
in the original. Therefore, the Ministry of Posts and 
Telecommunications maintains its position that "the government 
will not guarantee the private sector's implementation of 
investment in mobile phone systems and facilities" (according to 
a senior Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications official). 
  It seems, however, that the United States is basing its 
contention that the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications has 
guaranteed the private sector's numerical targets on the word 
used in the agreement. It has also been disclosed that in the 
recent accord, it is specified that Japan "will take all 
available measures" if IDO fails to implement its pledged 
action. Such a difference between the two nations's ways of 
interpreting the statement described in the accord on mobile 
phones is another "vague" point in a Japanese-U.S. agreement. 
It is likely that such a difference in interpretation will have 
a delicate impact on Japan-U.S. negotiations on other trade 
sectors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5270 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas069__a94005" </HT>


