<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   USTR Kantor Reportedly Mutes Trade Criticism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    USTR Kantor Reportedly Mutes Trade Criticism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0904122994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0904122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Hiroaki Ito] </F>
  [Text] Washington -- U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor, who has made "Japan bashing" a daily task, recently 
stopped making critical comments on Japan. He is believed to 
have changed his comments on Japan out of concern that if his 
criticism of Japan spurs further appreciation of the yen against 
the U.S. dollar, this may result in higher interest rates and 
lower stock prices in the United States at a time when fears are 
rising of a crash on the New York Stock Exchange. 
  In his lecture to a gathering of medium and small businesses 
on 5 April, Mr. Kantor only cited the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks as an example of U.S. efforts to open foreign 
markets. In his lecture he did not mention the "closed nature 
of the Japanese market," a term that he has frequently used. 
  Foreign investors rushed to U.S. stock markets in search of 
profits from a rise in stock prices after interest rates were 
lowered last autumn in the United States, but they recently 
began suffering losses in their stock holdings in the wake of a 
recent rebound in interest rates and a plunge in stock prices. 
  If the yen appreciates further against the U.S. dollar in 
this situation, foreign investors would suffer another loss from 
the fluctuation of the exchange rate between the yen and dollar. 
A major Japanese securities firm says, "Under the present 
situation, we want to pull out of U.S. stock markets after 
selling off our stock holdings even if we risk losses." 
  The U.S. Government is conspicuously jittery about the rise 
in interest rates and the plunge in stock prices. Robert Rubin, 
chairman of the National Economic Council (NEC), appearing on 
television on 3 April; Tyson, chairman of the Council of 
Economic Advisers; and President Clinton, speaking on television 
on 4 April, appealed to investors to respond calmly to plunging 
stock prices. Mr. Kantor appears to be "taciturn" about Japan as 
a result. 
  If the present situation continues, the U.S. Government will 
be pressed to alter its strategy toward Japan that aims at using 
the Super 301 provision to apply pressure on Japan. 
  It has been said within the U.S. Government that the "United 
States should pursue closer policy coordination with Japan and 
European nations to keep the rise in long-term interest rates in 
check, and curb further plunges in stock prices." Hence, there 
is a possibility that the low stock prices and the high interest 
rates in the United States will be taken up as an agenda item 
for discussion at the talks of G-7 financial ministers and 
central bank governors scheduled to be held in late April. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5272 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas069__a94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-069-A </AU>
