<H3> <TI>   Opposition Group Demands Government Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Group Demands Government Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804142694 Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME in English 1310 GMT 8 Apr 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0804142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, April 8 (OANA-MONTSAME) -- The 
representatives of the Mongolian Democratic Association (MDA) 
have demanded a resignation of the government at the meeting 
organized by the MDA at one of the central squares of the 
capital. 
  Those speaking at the meeting including the leaders of the 
MDA and people delegating the Social Democratic Party, the 
Students Union as well as the unemployed and pensioners have 
reminded the government all its promises concerning the 
stabilization of the national economy within a two-year period 
and criticized the policies being pursued by the government in 
the spheres of foreign trade, social welfare of the population, 
production and finance. 
  It was said that the abuses of official position are 
acquiring a boundless character at any level of management. In 
this connection some speakers stressed the significance of the 
hearing of the issue on possible involvement of some leaders of 
the parliament and government in corruption and abuses of 
official position to be carried out as sooner as possible. 
  The chairman of the parliament and the prime minister 
refused 
to take part in the meeting though they had been invited to it 
by the organizers of the meeting. The leaders of the MDA 
explained their suggestion as striving to provide the leaders of 
the country with possibilities to express their opinions and to 
be associated with the common people. 
  When the meeting was over, its participants passed to the 
main square of the capital named after D. Suhbaatar where those 
who wanted could express their views from the "free rostrum" 
arranged by the MDA. 
  The meeting was attended by not less than five-six [as 
received] thousand people. 

</TEXT>

