<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defector Says Missile Sites Located Near PRC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defector Says Missile Sites Located Near PRC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804150594 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0804150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sadashi Kiyoda] </F>
  [Text] Seoul, 7 April -- It was disclosed recently that 
the DPRK is building large missile launching sites in areas near 
the Chinese border. This was disclosed to an ASAHI SHIMBUN 
reporter by former North Korean Lieutenant Yim Yong-son who has 
taken refuge in the ROK. Reportedly, the DPRK chose the areas 
thinking that other countries would not dare to attack the sites 
for fear of bombing China by mistake. 
  Former Lieutenant Yim worked at the military construction 
bureau in Pyongyang till he defected to the ROK last September. 
According to his fellow soldier who was engaged in the 
construction of missile bases, the launch sites are located 
mainly in the eastern coastal areas, including North Hamgyong 
and Kangwon Provinces and Wonsan City. Recently, however, the 
DPRK started to construct missile sites along the Chinese 
border. It is said that about 5,000 people are working at the 
sites at Chunggangjin in Changang Province and that the job will 
be completed next year. Former Lieutenant Yim said: "I heard 
that the DPRK selected the areas presuming that it would be 
difficult for the United States and the ROK to launch an attack 
in time of emergency for fear of hitting China by accident." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

