<F P=101> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Do Muoi Receives Japanese Business Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Do Muoi Receives Japanese Business Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0704223394 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 6 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0704223394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Koji Takeuchi] </F>
  [Text] A delegation of the Japan-Vietnam Economic Committee 
(chairman: Akira Nishio, president of the Nissho Iwai 
Corporation) of the Federation of Economic Organizations of 
Japan [Keidanren] is now on a visit to Vietnam. The delegation 
paid a call on Do Muoi, Communist Party of Vietnam general 
secretary, in Hanoi on 5 April. During the meeting with members 
of the delegation, the Vietnamese leader stated: "Japan is 
Vietnam's biggest trading partner and a top aid donor of 
Vietnam. I am grateful to Japan. The amount of investment in 
Vietnam from the Japanese private sector remains small, 
however." In this way, he asked for Japan's increased 
investment in Vietnam. Specifically, he asked Japan to invest 
in Vietnam's machinery industry, which can generate employment, 
transfer high technology to Vietnam, and provide Vietnam with 
business management know-how. 
  In response, Chairman Nishio said, "Japan's investment in 
Vietnam lags behind that of other nations, but Japan will be a 
top investor in Vietnam sometime in the future." Thus, the 
Japanese business leader indicated that in taking advantage of 
the lifting of the U.S. embargo against Vietnam, Japan would 
make aggressive investments in Vietnam in the future. 

</TEXT>

