<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Foreign Minister `Secretly' Meets Blix </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Foreign Minister `Secretly' Meets Blix </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204130594 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1026 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1204130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "News 7" program] </F>
  [Text] ROK Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu and Director 
General Hans Blix of the International Atomic Energy Agency 
[IAEA] secretly met today in a hotel near Narita Airport in 
Tokyo, and discussed the issue of the DPRK's, or North Korea's, 
nuclear facilities. 
  Foreign Minister Han landed at Narita Airport today, one day 
earlier than the scheduled stopover for his week-long visit to 
Russia, to meet Director General Blix, who had just arrived in 
Tokyo to attend an international conference. 
  The meeting was not opened to the press in view of North 
Korea's intensified criticism of the IAEA policies. The topics 
for discussion at the meeting are unknown, but it is believed 
that the two leaders discussed such issues as results of the 
IAEA inspections in North Korea last month and possibilities of 
North Korea's acceptance of the IAEA inspections in the future. 
  [Begin Blix recording] We talked about the need for the 
IAEA's early completion of inspections in the regions resisting 
them. [end recording] 
  Concerning the question of North Korea's nuclear development 
program, U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry is scheduled to 
visit Japan and the ROK next week. Nations concerned including 
Japan, have begun to move actively in preparation for the UN 
Security Council session in early May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

