<H3> <TI>   Kazakhstan's Nazarbayev: No Policy Change </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kazakhstan's Nazarbayev: No Policy Change </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0904071694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0657 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0904071694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 9 KYODO -- Kazakhstan's President 
Nursultan Nazarbayev said Saturday [9 April] that Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa's resignation will not alter Japanese policy 
or affect agreements signed between the two countries. 
Nazarbayev told reporters at a Tokyo hotel that bilateral 
agreements will remain valid and projects planned between 
Japanese corporations and his country will remain unchanged. 
  Nazarbayev said that Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
announcement Friday that he will resign was unexpected but did 
not come as a surprise. He said he received no prior indication 
that Hosokawa would announce his resignation when he met the 
prime minister on Thursday. 
  But Nazarbayev said he is aware that "when a large number of 
parties make up a coalition, the problems usually become complex. 
  "From an international perspective, it (Hosokawa's 
resignation) is nothing to be surprised about," he said. 
  Nazarbayev arrived in Japan on Wednesday for a four-day 
visit. In addition to his talks with Hosokawa, Nazarbayev met 
Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko on Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

