<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Ouchi: Watanabe `Unlikely' Choice </H4>

<F P=102> OW1204074094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0646 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- The leader of the 
Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), a group in the ruling 
coalition, said Tuesday [12 April] that former Foreign Minister 
Michio Watanabe of the opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) 
is unlikely to be chosen as a successor to outgoing Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  DSP Chairman Keigo Ouchi said, "Mr. Watanabe is outside the 
framework of the coalition. I have heard there is considerable 
criticism and rejection from opposition and ruling parties 
(against Watanabe's premiership). It's not so easy." 
  "Even if Mr. Watanabe would join the current ruling parties, 
how many people can he bring (from the LDP)? I doubt the number 
reaches as high as rumored. In that case, it would be quite 
difficult for the ruling parties to secure the majority (in the 
511-seat House of Representatives)," said Ouchi, the health and 
welfare minister. 
  A senior official of the LDP's Watanabe faction said Monday 
that Watanabe plans to form a new parliamentary group in the 
lower house in a bid to form a coalition government with three 
ruling parties -- Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], Komeito and 
the Japan New Party (JNP). 
  As the combined parliamentary strength of Watanabe's 
46-member faction, Shinseito, Komeito and the JNP stands at 161, 
Watanabe will need to win support from more than 95 LDP 
legislators who belong to other LDP factions in order to hold 
the majority seats. 
  Since last February, Watanabe has repeatedly held meetings 
with Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa, who is regarded 
as the chief coalition strategist. 
  Shinseito and Komeito -- key forces within the ruling 
coalition -- are widely deemed as willing to name Watanabe the 
next leader of a new coalition government in an attempt to oust 
the Social Democratic Party and new party Sakigake [Harbinger] 
from the coalition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

