<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kono Intends `Fair Fight' </H4>

<F P=102> OW1204030794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0252 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204030794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- Opposition leader Yohei 
Kono indicated Tuesday that he intends to put himself forward as 
a candidate when the Diet chooses the next prime minister. He 
told a meeting of Liberal Democratic Party executives that LDP 
members should unite in the election, party officials said. 
  But he said he intends to have a "fair fight" with the 
ruling 
coalition, which has yet to choose its candidate to succeed 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who announced his intention to 
step down last Friday. 
  Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of the LDP, supported Kono, 
saying it is natural for a party leader to run for the 
premiership, the officials said. 
  Kono rapped moves within the LDP to put forward former 
Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe for the premiership, insisting 
that he as party president should be the candidate. 
  Backers of Watanabe argued that the party president need not 
be the automatic candidate, and Taku Yamasaki, deputy general 
secretary of the party, voiced opposition to Kono's comments. 
Yamasaki belongs to an LDP faction headed by Watanabe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5490 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas070_a_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Coalition Moves To Avert Split </H4>

<F P=102> OW1204132894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1248 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- The governing coalition on 
Tuesday [12 April] took a step toward averting a split over the 
picking of a successor to departing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, top coalition officials said. 
  "I'm pretty sure we can solve our problems to maintain and 
develop our coalition government," Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
Secretary General Wataru Kubo told a news conference. 
  Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party) Secretary General Ichiro 
Ozawa, a top coalition strategist, also told reporters, 
"everything is going in the right direction," in a reference to 
the bickering among coalition partners over procedures to choose 
a replacement for Hosokawa. 
  At a session of their caucus on Tuesday evening, coalition 
executives concurred on the need to work out differences between 
them and coalition party leaders on the succession procedures, 
Kubo said. The top coalition officials will meet again on 
Wednesday morning to discuss the matter further, he said, adding 
he believes they can get down to the nitty-gritty of picking a 
candidate for the premiership from Wednesday. 
  While new party Sakigake (Harbinger), the Democratic 
Socialist Party (DSP) and the SDP favor the selection of a new 
premier at a forum of coalition chiefs, Shinseito, Komeito and 
Hosokawa's Japan New Party (JNP) contend the secretary 
general-level caucus should first discuss the matter. 
  Hosokawa, who remains in office until his successor is 
picked, had asked the coalition executives' forum to take charge 
of the selection business. 
  Earlier Tuesday, leaders of four coalition components met 
for 
a second time since Monday and shared the view that coalition 
chiefs should first discuss how to choose a candidate for the 
next premiership. 
  The four were Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura of 
Sakigake, Health and Welfare Minister Keigo Ouchi of the DSP, 
SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama and Eiichi Nakamura of the 
Democratic Reform Party, a small parliamentary group in the 
House of Councillors. 
  Murayama twice proposed holding a meeting of coalition 
chiefs, once on Monday and again on Tuesday, to break the 
gridlock over the choice of a new premier, which poses a threat 
to the unity within the eight-month-old coalition. But leaders 
of four coalition partners -- Shinseito, Komeito, the JNP and 
the United Social Democratic Party -- rejected the bid and 
boycotted the two sessions. 
  The row over the procedures to find Hosokawa's replacement 
clearly revealed the deep gulf between the moderate-to-leftist 
Sakigake-DSP-SDP bloc and the more conservative 
Shinseito-Komeito camp over political philosophies and some 
fundamental national policies. 
  The known personal rivalry between Shinseito's Ozawa and 
Sakigake chief Takemura has also fueled the coalition's 
polarization into two blocs. 
  While hoping to install Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, who 
heads Shinseito, as the new premier, the latter alliance has 
also been considering fielding former Foreign Minister Michio 
Watanabe of the opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) as a 
candidate to succeed Hosokawa. 
  Watanabe, whose close personal relationship with Ozawa is no 
secret, has signaled his readiness to run for the highest 
government office. 
  The Shinseito-Komeito bloc would give the boot to the SDP, 
the largest coalition contingent whose basic policies are still 
far apart from those of other coalition partners, should 
Watanabe decide to quit the LDP with a large number of his 
followers and join a part of the coalition, political sources 
said. 
  The ex-foreign minister said Tuesday he wishes to run for 
the 
premiership, "with an irreversible determination," even by 
launching a new party, said Seiichi Ota, a close associate of 
Watanabe. 
  While Watanabe's supporters are waging a campaign to have 
their boss selected as the LDP's candidate for the premiership, 
LDP President Yohei Kono himself vowed Tuesday to run in the 
parliamentary election to pick Hosokawa's successor. 
  The two men will meet Wednesday to exchange views on the 
selection of a replacement for Hosokawa, party officials said. 
  Sakigake, for its part, also showed interest in forming a 
tie-up with pro-reformers within the LDP, which was ousted from 
power last August for the first time in 38 years. Sakigake is 
an LDP breakaway party. 
  As the possibility increased of neither of the two plans 
bearing fruit, however, the squabbling coalition parties began 
moving to mend fences and maintain the current framework of 
their alliance. 
  "We faced a problem concerning the basis of the coalition 
this time," Kubo said. "I believe the coalition will grow 
solidified by overcoming problems like this." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5491 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas070_a_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Coalition Split Deepens on Issue </H4>

<F P=102> OW1204064394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0631 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- The split in the governing 
coalition deepened Tuesday over how to pick a successor to Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa who announced his resignation last 
Friday, coalition sources said. 
  Leaders of three out of the seven parties in the coalition 
met again in the Diet, following the one on Monday. They were 
the heads of the Social Democratic Party (SDP), the new party 
Sakigake and the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP). The head of 
a pro-SDP group in the House of Councillors, the Democratic 
Reform Party (DRP), joined the session. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiich Murayama, Sakigake leader Masayoshi 
Takemura and DSP Chairman Keigo Ouchi, DRP leader Eiichi 
Nakamura agreed in the meeting that they will never give the 
mandate on the choice of Hosokawa's successor to a lower-level 
forum made up of secretaries general, coalition officials said. 
  Heads of four other parties -- Shinseito, Komeito, the Japan 
New Party (JNP), and the United Social Democratic Party (USDP) 
-- again boycotted the top leaders' session proposed by the 
SDP's Murayama, arguing that the matter should first be 
discussed at the secretary general-level forum. They are 
Tsutomu Hata of Shinseito, Koshiro Ishida of Komeito, Hosokawa 
of the JNP, and Satsuki Eda of the USDP. 
  The SDP, Sakigake and DSP are wary that Shinseito Secretary 
General Ichiro Ozawa and Komeito Secretary General Yuichi 
Ichikawa may take the leading role in the secretary 
general-level discussions over the choice of the successor. 
  After the three party leaders gave their blessings to 
Murayama's proposal to reserve the mandate to pick the new 
premier for themselves, the SDP-led camp conveyed its stand to 
the Shinseito-led forum, adding fuel to the intra-coalition 
hostilities. 
  Murayama, Takemura, Ouchi and Nakamura also agreed to band 
again whenever necessary, while monitoring how the Shinseito-led 
caucus would respond to their claim for the mandate, coalition 
officials said. 
  The Shinseito-led caucus has been insisting upon its 
authority to pick the coalition's next prime ministerial 
candidate on the strength of a statement by Hosokawa that he 
wants the caucus to take charge of decision-making on the 
"remaining" matters, they said. 
  However, Murayama rejected their interpretation, saying, 
"the 
premier's remark merely implied that he wants the caucus to take 
care of the remaining small businesses (until a next premier is 
picked)." 
  "In selecting the prime minister of a country, the meeting 
of 
the deputy chiefs of the parties should not be given the mandate 
to pick the premier," Murayama told the other three leaders from 
Sakigake, the DSP and the DRP. 
  Takemura told the top leaders meeting, "although I agree to 
make efforts to maintain the current combination, I want them 
(the Shiseito-led caucus) to feel repentant and amend the 
attitudes they have taken over the past eight months." 
  A Komeito official said of the rising intra-coalition 
standoff, "now it is impossible to mend fences." 
  "We cannot help altering a combination of political parties 
that comprise the ruling coalition government," he said. 
  Shinseito head Hata, who is the foreign minister, denied 
reports that the coalition is on the brink of collapse. 
  Hata told a news conference Tuesday, "it's true that various 
emotions are entangled." "But if we go back to the starting 
point of why we established the coalition, I think we can 
restore it." 
  JNP leader Hosokawa indicated there will be a recombination 
of parties in the eight-month-old ruling coalition, telling some 
party legislators "the coalition needs to accept a new group." 
  A separate standoff is beginning to undercut the solidarity 
of the No. 1 opposition party, the Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP), party sources said. 
  While the backers of former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe 
are waging a campaign to have him selected as the LDP's 
candidate for premiership, LDP President Yohei Kono announced 
his intention to run for premiership himself. 
  The LDP, the single largest party in the House of 
Representatives with a 219-legislator parliamentary strength, 
now stands a chance of sweeping back to power on the strength of 
the growing intra-coalition animosity, political sources said. 
  The majority in the 511-member lower chamber is 256. 
Watanabe backers said they have solicited the support from more 
than 40 LDP legislators by Tuesday. 
  If Watanabe wants to sweep to power as the head of a new 
coalition government, he needs to muster support of about 100 
LDP legislators, on top of the allegiance of the combined 
156-member strength of his own LDP faction, Shinseito, Komeito 
and the JNP, which are deemed to be ready to lend their support 
to Watanabe, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

