<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Controversy Over Successor to Hosokawa Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata: Coalition Not Collapsing </H4>

<F P=102> OW1204025994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0247 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204025994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata denied suggestions Tuesday that the ruling coalition is on 
the brink of collapse over choosing a successor to outgoing 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Hata, who is also a leader of Shinseito, one of the ruling 
parties, told a press conference the coalition has not broken up 
because meetings of the senior executives of the parties are 
still being held. "It's true that various emotions are 
entangled," Hata said. "But if we go back to the starting point 
of why we established the coalition, I think we can restore it." 
  He added that the coalition has solved various difficult 
problems since it came to power eight months ago. 
  The seven-party coalition is at odds over at what level to 
decide on a candidate to replace Hosokawa. The Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) called for a meeting of all the coalition 
party heads, but Shinseito, Komeito and the Japan New Party 
rejected the call. 
  Hata said Shinseito has already voiced its opinion in the 
executives' meeting that a meeting of the top leaders should be 
left to the last in deciding the succession issue. He suggested 
a meeting of executives and top leaders of the coalition 
together. 

</TEXT>

