<H3> <TI>   LDP Reform-Minded Members Urged To Quit Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDP Reform-Minded Members Urged To Quit Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204084894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0820 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- Two Diet members of the 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) are urging reform-minded members 
in the main opposition party to quit and form a new party, the 
ASAHI SHIMBUN reported Tuesday. The mass-circulation daily 
named the two as Michihiko Kano and Masayasu Kitagawa, both of 
whom have pushed for political and electoral reforms. 
  Kano, Kitagawa and their supporters are expected to leave 
the 
LDP in a day or two, at the earliest, the ASAHI said in its 
evening edition. 
  Kano has served as director general of the Management and 
Coordination Agency, while Kitagawa was once parliamentary vice 
minister of education. The two men are lobbying some 40 LDP 
legislators to join a new party they want to set up, and hope to 
get at least 20 members for it, the newspaper said without 
attribution. 
  Kitagawa is known for his close ties with new party Sakigake 
leader Masayoshi Takemura, who is the chief cabinet secretary. 
The pair plan to keep their distance from both the LDP and the 
ruling coalition, it said. 

