<F P=103> OW0804025394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 8 KYODO -- Planned hikes in utility 
and other public service charges are unlikely to put a damper on 
the economy, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii said Friday [8 
April]. 
  The government has allowed in its economic forecast for a 
1.5 
percent rise in domestic prices stemming from the hikes provided 
for in the fiscal 1994 budget, Fujii told a regular news 
conference after a morning cabinet meeting. 
  The cabinet meeting reconfirmed the need to have related 
public utilities firms streamline their operations to avoid 
unnecessary rate hikes but did not decide to stop or squeeze the 
planned hikes. 
  Considering rate hikes proposed aside from the budget, Fujii 
said related ministries and agencies will decide on these based 
on the policy reconfirmed at the cabinet meeting. "There won't 
be much," he said. 

