<H3> <TI>   Fujii Says Economy in `Delicate Stage' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fujii Says Economy in `Delicate Stage' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204013394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0122 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204013394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 KYODO -- The latest statistics have 
yet not proved that the economy has hit bottom and prolonged 
political unrest may put a damper on public sentiment, Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii said Tuesday [12 April]. "The economy 
is in a delicate stage" with both good and bad indicators, Fujii 
repeated at a news conference after a morning cabinet meeting. 
  Fujii was referring to a monthly economic report endorsed at 
the cabinet meeting. The report, compiled by the Economic 
Planning Agency, said the economy remains sluggish but included 
a phrase that some bright spots have emerged. 
  Fujii's cautious stance on the economy contrasts with that 
of 
Bank of Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno and many private 
economists, who have recently suggested that the economy is 
showing signs of bottoming out. 
  The finance minister said the political uncertainty "is 
certainty not favorable" for corporate and consumer sentiment. 
He called for a settlement as soon as possible of the issue of 
choosing a successor to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who 
announced his intention to resign last Friday. 
  Concerning tax reform, Fujii said, "the direction and track 
indicated by the Hosokawa cabinet will be inherited by any new 
cabinet." 
  "Tax reform should become the mainstay of any new cabinet," 
he said. The government has pledged to conduct a full tax 
reform, including permanent income tax cuts, by the end of the 
year, and promised in its March market-opening package to 
present details of the tax reform plan in June. 
  Legislators of both the ruling parties and the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party attached a provision to include 
permanent tax cuts in the tax reform when they enacted a 
single-year tax cut bill in March. 

</TEXT>

